01:36.307 --> 01:37.850
[APPLAUSE STOPS]

01:54.450 --> 01:56.033
Hello.

01:56.118 --> 01:57.494
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Hi! We're ready.

02:00.540 --> 02:02.249
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

02:09.256 --> 02:10.842
One, two, three.

02:15.805 --> 02:20.267
I haven't seen you for many years,
since 1968.

02:21.561 --> 02:26.774
I have decided that I will
do no more jazz festivals.

02:27.775 --> 02:30.027
That decision has not changed.

02:31.738 --> 02:33.655
I will sing for you,

02:33.740 --> 02:38.077
or we will do and share with you
a few moments,

02:39.078 --> 02:43.372
after which I shall graduate
to a higher class, I hope,

02:43.457 --> 02:45.793
and I hope you will come with me.

02:46.711 --> 02:49.088
We will start from the beginning,

02:51.298 --> 02:53.635
which was about a little girl,

02:55.136 --> 02:56.971
and her name was Blue.

02:57.764 --> 03:00.182
[PLAYING "GOOD KING WENCESLAS"]

03:47.146 --> 03:48.605
[PLAYING FADES]

03:55.529 --> 03:57.448
[TAPE RECORDER ROLLING]

03:59.992 --> 04:01.408
INTERVIEWER: <i>What's "free" to you, Nina?</i>

04:01.493 --> 04:02.660
- <i>What's "free" to me?</i>
- <i>Yeah.</i>

04:02.745 --> 04:05.121
Same thing it is to you. You tell me.

04:05.206 --> 04:07.248
INTERVIEWER: No, no, you tell me.

04:07.333 --> 04:09.043
- [BOTH LAUGHING]
- INTERVIEWER: I don't know.

04:11.628 --> 04:14.005
It's just a feeling.

04:14.090 --> 04:16.339
It's just a feeling.

04:16.425 --> 04:19.510
It's like, "How do you tell somebody
how it feels to be in love?"

04:19.595 --> 04:22.554
How are you going to tell anybody
who has not been in love

04:22.639 --> 04:24.056
how it feels to be in love?

04:24.141 --> 04:26.308
You cannot do it to save your life.

04:26.393 --> 04:29.771
You can describe things
but you can't tell them,

04:29.856 --> 04:32.273
but you know it when it happens.

04:32.358 --> 04:33.941
That's what I mean by "free."

04:34.026 --> 04:37.612
I've had a couple of times onstage
when I really felt free,

04:37.697 --> 04:39.781
and that's something else.

04:39.866 --> 04:42.992
- [INTERVIEWER LAUGHS]
- That's really something else!

04:43.077 --> 04:46.245
Like, all... all... Like... like...

04:46.330 --> 04:49.792
I'll tell you what freedom
is to me, no fear.

04:52.128 --> 04:54.881
I mean, really, no fear.

04:56.048 --> 04:58.883
If I could have that

04:58.968 --> 05:02.887
half of my life, no fear.

05:02.972 --> 05:07.143
<i># I wish I could share #</i>

05:08.853 --> 05:11.939
<i># All the love that's in my heart #</i>

05:14.233 --> 05:18.237
<i># Remove all the bars #</i>

05:19.989 --> 05:23.785
<i># That still keep us apart #</i>

05:25.995 --> 05:29.749
<i># I wish you could know #</i>

05:30.792 --> 05:34.796
<i># What it means to be me #</i>

05:35.963 --> 05:41.258
<i># Then you'd see and agree #</i>

05:41.343 --> 05:45.973
<i># That every man should be free #</i>

05:47.308 --> 05:52.396
<i># I wish I could give #</i>

05:53.898 --> 05:56.899
<i># All I'm longing to give #</i>

05:56.984 --> 06:00.111
LISA SIMONE KELLY: <i>My mother was one</i>
<i>of the greatest entertainers of all time,</i>

06:00.196 --> 06:01.821
<i>hands down...</i>

06:01.906 --> 06:03.282
<i>but she paid a huge price.</i>

06:04.741 --> 06:07.618
People seem to think that
when she went out on stage,

06:07.703 --> 06:11.538
that was when she became Nina Simone.

06:11.623 --> 06:13.833
My mother was Nina Simone 24/7...

06:13.918 --> 06:18.005
<i>and that's where it became a problem.</i>

06:19.215 --> 06:24.468
- <i># One day I woke up and I could fly #</i>
- [CHORUS] <i># Yes, I know #</i>

06:24.553 --> 06:29.974
- <i># I'd look down at the sea #</i>
- <i># Yes, I know #</i>

06:30.059 --> 06:32.434
<i># And I wouldn’t know myself #</i>

06:32.519 --> 06:35.354
<i># I'd have new hands #</i>

06:35.439 --> 06:40.526
- <i># I’d have new feet #</i>
- <i># Yes, I know #</i>

06:40.611 --> 06:46.115
- <i># I’d have new vision #</i>
- <i># Yes, I know #</i>

06:46.200 --> 06:52.539
- <i># My eyes would be open a little better #</i>
- <i># Yes, I know #</i>

06:53.540 --> 06:58.961
LISA: <i>When she was performing,</i>
<i>she was brilliant, she was loved.</i>

06:59.046 --> 07:01.130
<i>She was also a revolutionary.</i>

07:01.215 --> 07:04.258
<i>She found a purpose for the stage,</i>

07:04.343 --> 07:10.264
<i>a place from which she could
use her voice to speak out for her people.</i>

07:10.349 --> 07:13.434
- <i># Don't get in my way #</i>
- <i># Yes, I know #</i>

07:13.519 --> 07:15.104
[AUDIENCE CLAPPING AND CHEERING]

07:19.400 --> 07:22.734
<i>But when the show ended,
everybody else went home.</i>

07:22.819 --> 07:26.405
<i>She was alone
and she was still fighting...</i>

07:26.490 --> 07:29.700
<i>but she was fighting her own demons...</i>

07:29.785 --> 07:32.579
<i>full of anger and rage.</i>

07:34.123 --> 07:36.500
<i>She couldn't live with herself...</i>

07:37.626 --> 07:39.128
and everything fell apart.

07:39.795 --> 07:43.257
<i># For one moment of my whole life #</i>

07:45.259 --> 07:47.386
<i># I would know how #</i>

07:49.263 --> 07:51.723
<i># It would feel #</i>

07:55.186 --> 08:00.607
<i># To be free #</i>

08:11.327 --> 08:14.620
INTERVIEWER: <i>Good evening.</i>
<i>Our guest tonight is Nina Simone.</i>

08:14.705 --> 08:19.083
<i>Probably the foremost blues singer,
jazz singer, singer of all songs</i>

08:19.168 --> 08:20.626
<i>in the United States today.</i>

08:20.711 --> 08:24.296
<i>Nina, are you happy with
the kind of work you are doing?</i>

08:24.381 --> 08:26.507
NINA: <i>What makes me the happiest,</i>

08:26.592 --> 08:29.886
<i>is when I'm performing
and there are people out there</i>

08:29.971 --> 08:33.264
<i>who feel with me
and I know I touched them.</i>

08:33.349 --> 08:35.349
<i>But to be completely honest,</i>

08:35.433 --> 08:38.477
<i>the whole thing
seems so much like a dream.</i>

08:38.562 --> 08:41.981
<i>I never thought I was gonna
stay in show business.</i>

08:42.066 --> 08:44.025
<i>When I first got into show business,</i>

08:44.110 --> 08:47.111
<i>I wasn't a blues singer
and I wasn't even a jazz singer.</i>

08:47.196 --> 08:49.280
<i>I was a classical pianist.</i>

08:49.365 --> 08:50.614
<i>I studied to become</i>

08:50.699 --> 08:53.993
<i>the first black classical pianist
in America,</i>

08:54.078 --> 08:56.412
<i>and that's all that was on my mind.</i>

08:56.497 --> 08:59.833
<i>That's what I was prepared to be.</i>

09:00.417 --> 09:03.961
<i>I was born Eunice Waymon,
which is my real name, by the way,</i>

09:04.046 --> 09:07.589
<i>in a town called Tryon, North Carolina.</i>

09:07.674 --> 09:11.886
<i>I started to play the piano
when I was three or four.</i>

09:11.971 --> 09:14.055
<i>My mother was a preacher</i>

09:14.140 --> 09:18.225
<i>and she took me with her on her revivals,</i>

09:18.310 --> 09:20.937
<i>and I started to play the piano in church.</i>

09:21.022 --> 09:22.982
["CHILDREN GO WHERE I SEND YOU" PLAYING]

09:26.027 --> 09:28.986
<i># Children go where I send you #</i>

09:29.071 --> 09:30.821
<i># How shall I send you? #</i>

09:30.906 --> 09:33.574
<i># I'm gonna send you one by one #</i>

09:33.659 --> 09:39.956
<i># One for the little biddy baby
was born, born, born in Bethlehem #</i>

09:40.041 --> 09:43.960
<i>Revival meetings were
some of the most exciting times</i>

09:44.045 --> 09:46.003
<i>that I've ever had.</i>

09:46.088 --> 09:48.172
<i>The music was so intense,</i>

09:48.257 --> 09:50.841
<i>you just sort of went out of yourself.</i>

09:50.926 --> 09:52.176
<i>I felt it tremendously.</i>

09:52.261 --> 09:53.720
<i>I was leading it.</i>

09:55.181 --> 10:00.267
<i>When I was seven, the choir of our church
gave a program at the local theater,</i>

10:00.352 --> 10:03.687
<i>and I was on that program...</i>

10:03.772 --> 10:06.190
<i>And I played some song,
I don't remember what it was,</i>

10:06.275 --> 10:10.277
<i>and these two women, two white women,
in the audience heard me.</i>

10:10.362 --> 10:12.821
<i>One of them was the woman
that my mother worked for,</i>

10:12.906 --> 10:16.575
<i>and the other one was a music teacher,
Mrs. Mazzanovich,</i>

10:16.660 --> 10:19.536
<i>and they decided right then and there
to give me lessons.</i>

10:19.621 --> 10:22.414
<i>And so, for five years after that,</i>

10:22.499 --> 10:26.087
<i>I studied piano, classical piano,
with this teacher.</i>

10:30.924 --> 10:35.177
<i>I crossed the railroad tracks
every weekend to get to Mrs. Mazzanovich.</i>

10:35.262 --> 10:36.803
<i>And, you know,
railroad tracks in the South</i>

10:36.888 --> 10:39.098
<i>are supposed to be dividing
the blacks from the whites.</i>

10:39.183 --> 10:40.351
<i>Well, it really did.</i>

10:41.268 --> 10:43.227
<i>I was so scared.</i>

10:43.312 --> 10:45.896
<i>Mrs. Mazzanovich frightened me.</i>

10:45.981 --> 10:50.901
<i>It was her being white,
in the sense that I had never seen.</i>

10:50.986 --> 10:52.861
<i>She was alien to me.</i>

10:52.946 --> 10:56.700
<i>Her white hair, the combs in it,
her pleasantness...</i>

10:57.284 --> 10:59.160
<i>I loved that.</i>

10:59.245 --> 11:01.370
<i>And she started me on Bach.</i>

11:01.455 --> 11:04.250
<i>And this Bach, I liked him.</i>

11:09.088 --> 11:11.130
<i>Mrs. Mazzanovich had it in her mind</i>

11:11.215 --> 11:15.217
<i>that I was gonna be one of
the world's greatest concert pianists.</i>

11:15.302 --> 11:18.845
<i>So it was all
very disciplined classical music.</i>

11:18.930 --> 11:23.016
<i>Bach, Beethoven, Debussy,
Brahms, you name it.</i>

11:23.101 --> 11:27.813
<i>Then Mrs. Mazzanovich got a fund together,
"Eunice Waymon Fund,"</i>

11:27.898 --> 11:29.898
<i>and I gave lots of recitals,</i>

11:29.983 --> 11:34.530
<i>and they would take up collection to
further my education after I had left her.</i>

11:35.656 --> 11:39.075
LISA: <i>Mommy took to all of the training</i>
<i>like a fish to water,</i>

11:39.160 --> 11:40.867
<i>but it was a double-edged sword.</i>

11:40.952 --> 11:42.536
She had a very lonely life

11:42.621 --> 11:46.039
<i>because she was practicing
seven, eight hours a day.</i>

11:46.124 --> 11:47.999
NINA:
<i>When I first started to take lessons,</i>

11:48.084 --> 11:53.422
<i>I became terribly aware of how isolated
I was from the other children,</i>

11:53.507 --> 11:59.136
<i>and how isolated I was from the white
community and the negro community.</i>

11:59.221 --> 12:02.931
<i>I felt it, all the time,
even when the kids used to play with me.</i>

12:03.016 --> 12:06.393
<i>They always wanted me
just to play the piano for them to dance.</i>

12:06.478 --> 12:09.313
<i>I wasn't asked too much
to do anything else.</i>

12:09.398 --> 12:12.568
<i>That was very hard.</i>

12:13.569 --> 12:17.030
<i>Part of that isolation, of course,
was the thing about color.</i>

12:17.948 --> 12:21.158
<i>I was a black girl, and I knew about it,
and I lived in it.</i>

12:21.243 --> 12:23.287
<i>I lived in the South for 17 years.</i>

12:25.038 --> 12:27.664
LISA: <i>My mom rarely referred</i>
<i>to Jim Crow and segregation</i>

12:27.749 --> 12:32.836
<i>and a lot of the racial issues that
were going on at that stage in her life.</i>

12:32.921 --> 12:35.922
But she did tell me about times
when she was told her nose was too big,

12:36.007 --> 12:38.219
her lips were too full
and her skin was too dark.

12:39.135 --> 12:41.637
<i>And after she was told that,
they probably told her,</i>

12:41.722 --> 12:45.391
<i>"There's only certain things
you'll be good for in your life."</i>

12:45.476 --> 12:47.601
NINA: <i>What I knew, I knew.</i>

12:47.686 --> 12:51.062
<i>But we weren't allowed to mention
anything racial in our house.</i>

12:51.147 --> 12:53.899
<i>I wasn't consciously dealing with race.</i>

12:53.984 --> 12:56.278
<i>That wasn't consciously
on my mind at all...</i>

12:56.862 --> 12:58.864
<i>until years later.</i>

13:03.827 --> 13:06.119
<i>After I graduated from high school,</i>

13:06.204 --> 13:09.623
<i>the money that had been saved
from the Eunice Waymon Fund</i>

13:09.708 --> 13:14.880
<i>sent me to New York to Juilliard
for a year and a half.</i>

13:15.797 --> 13:21.927
<i>And then I applied for a scholarship to
Curtis Institute of Music in Philadelphia.</i>

13:22.012 --> 13:26.348
<i>I was playing Czerny and Liszt
and Rachmaninoff and Bach.</i>

13:26.433 --> 13:31.102
<i>I knew I was good enough,
but they turned me down,</i>

13:31.187 --> 13:36.858
<i>and it took me about six months
to realize it was because I was black.</i>

13:36.943 --> 13:43.074
<i>I never really got over
that jolt of racism at the time.</i>

13:45.702 --> 13:47.453
<i>Then the money ran out</i>

13:47.538 --> 13:50.747
<i>and the reality hit me
that I had to go to work.</i>

13:50.832 --> 13:55.877
<i>My parents had moved the whole family
to Philadelphia to be near me,</i>

13:55.962 --> 13:59.130
<i>and my family is very poor,
so I had to work.</i>

13:59.215 --> 14:00.882
<i>What else was there for me to do?</i>

14:00.967 --> 14:05.178
<i>So, I got myself a job
in Atlantic City for a summer.</i>

14:05.263 --> 14:07.766
<i>It was a very crummy bar</i>

14:08.517 --> 14:12.728
<i>and I used to go in in evening gowns.
I didn't know any better.</i>

14:12.813 --> 14:15.272
<i>And I played everything
that I could think of.</i>

14:15.357 --> 14:18.775
<i>Pop songs, classical,
spirituals, all kinds of things.</i>

14:18.860 --> 14:21.195
<i>It was very strange.</i>

14:21.280 --> 14:23.530
<i>And I had never sung before,</i>

14:23.615 --> 14:25.324
<i>and the owner came in the second night</i>

14:25.409 --> 14:28.870
<i>and told me if I wanted to keep the job,
I had to sing.</i>

14:31.748 --> 14:35.876
<i>So, $90 was more money
than I had ever heard of in my life,</i>

14:35.961 --> 14:39.214
<i>so I said, "Well, I'll sing,"
and ever since then, I've been singing.</i>

14:42.468 --> 14:46.136
ROGER NUPIE: <i>Eunice Waymon was playing</i>
<i>in the bars to support her family</i>

14:46.221 --> 14:50.891
<i>and to have money to continue
her classical piano training.</i>

14:50.976 --> 14:52.643
But since she didn't want
her mother to know that

14:52.728 --> 14:56.104
she was playing
"the devil's music" in bars,

14:56.189 --> 14:58.815
<i>she changed her name.</i>

14:58.900 --> 15:01.194
<i>Eunice Waymon became Nina Simone.</i>

15:02.613 --> 15:05.572
<i>She named herself</i> "Niña,"
<i>meaning "little one,"</i>

15:05.657 --> 15:08.116
<i>and she had a boyfriend</i>
<i>who called her</i> "Niña,"

15:08.201 --> 15:12.956
<i>and "Simone" came from
the French actress Simone Signoret.</i>

15:13.874 --> 15:15.582
NINA: <i>I didn't want my mother to find out.</i>

15:15.667 --> 15:17.418
<i>I knew she would hate it.</i>

15:17.503 --> 15:22.381
<i>So I, kind of, kept it from her
for a long, long time.</i>

15:22.466 --> 15:24.090
INTERVIEWER: <i>Was it lonely</i>
<i>for a young girl</i>

15:24.175 --> 15:25.842
<i>entertaining in these strange bars?</i>

15:25.927 --> 15:27.886
NINA: <i>Extremely. Extremely lonely.</i>

15:27.971 --> 15:29.846
INTERVIEWER:
<i>Working peculiar hours, I imagine.</i>

15:29.931 --> 15:32.057
NINA:
<i>12:00 midnight to 7:00 in the morning.</i>

15:32.142 --> 15:33.725
INTERVIEWER:
<i>It ruined your social life, uh...</i>

15:33.810 --> 15:35.018
NINA: <i>Never had much of one.</i>

15:35.103 --> 15:38.272
INTERVIEWER: <i>Why'd you keep on with it?</i>
NINA: <i>Couldn't help it.</i>

15:38.357 --> 15:41.483
<i>I have to play and I needed money.</i>

15:41.568 --> 15:47.113
<i>It was always a matter of necessity
from day to day what I'm going to do.</i>

15:47.198 --> 15:49.240
<i>I didn't even know I was
going to stay in show business.</i>

15:49.325 --> 15:51.535
<i>I never thought about a choice.</i>

15:51.620 --> 15:58.544
NINA: [SINGING] <i># Nobody's fault but mine #</i>

16:01.630 --> 16:05.924
AL SCHACKMAN: <i>From the beginning,</i>
<i>I felt there was something eating at her.</i>

16:06.009 --> 16:08.677
You know, "What's eating at you, Nina?"

16:08.762 --> 16:10.138
And, um...

16:11.973 --> 16:14.267
gradually that got stronger.

16:16.395 --> 16:21.107
<i># For all we know #</i>

16:23.193 --> 16:30.158
<i># We may never meet again #</i>

16:32.703 --> 16:34.870
AL: <i>The first time I played with Nina,</i>

16:34.955 --> 16:40.584
<i>it was the summer of 1957
at a restaurant in New Hope, Pennsylvania.</i>

16:40.669 --> 16:42.168
She didn't look at me.

16:42.253 --> 16:45.213
Said nothing, as though I wasn't...
I wasn't even there,

16:45.298 --> 16:48.884
<i>and started in on a song.</i>

16:48.969 --> 16:50.844
<i>She never told me
what key she was going to be in.</i>

16:50.929 --> 16:54.681
<i>She just started playing, and I knew
exactly where I was going to go with it.</i>

16:54.766 --> 16:58.477
<i>It was like we had
a telepathic relationship.</i>

16:58.562 --> 17:01.312
<i>Before you knew it,
we were just weaving in and out.</i>

17:01.397 --> 17:03.942
And then she looked up.

17:04.568 --> 17:09.363
<i># Until... #</i>

17:09.448 --> 17:13.242
<i># ...the last minute #</i>

17:13.743 --> 17:17.496
NINA: <i>Al Schackman</i>
<i>is a terribly sensitive, creative man.</i>

17:17.580 --> 17:19.039
<i>He has perfect pitch,</i>

17:19.124 --> 17:21.583
<i>which means that
no matter what key I'm in,</i>

17:21.667 --> 17:25.295
<i>he's able to adapt himself immediately,
'cause I do that all the time.</i>

17:25.380 --> 17:28.133
<i>I'll change the key
in the middle of a tune.</i>

17:30.677 --> 17:35.681
AL: <i>Nina had a wonderful way</i>
<i>of taking a piece of music, and...</i>

17:35.766 --> 17:40.896
not interpreting it, but...
but, like, metamorphosizing it.

17:42.105 --> 17:46.026
You know, morphing it into her experience.

17:46.818 --> 17:53.700
<i># This may only be a dream #</i>

17:54.618 --> 17:58.829
NINA: <i>What I was interested in was</i>
<i>conveying an emotional message,</i>

17:58.914 --> 18:01.457
<i>which means using
everything you've got inside you</i>

18:01.542 --> 18:03.792
<i>sometimes to barely make a note</i>

18:03.877 --> 18:06.377
<i>or if you have to strain to sing,
you sing.</i>

18:06.462 --> 18:08.922
<i>So sometimes I sound like gravel,</i>

18:09.007 --> 18:12.092
<i>and sometimes
I sound like coffee and cream.</i>

18:12.177 --> 18:19.100
<i># So baby, love me, love me tonight #</i>

18:23.021 --> 18:29.945
<i># Tomorrow was made for some #</i>

18:33.448 --> 18:37.951
GEORGE WEIN: <i>When I first saw Nina</i>
<i>at my club in 1959,</i>

18:38.036 --> 18:40.370
<i>I was impressed. She was different.</i>

18:40.455 --> 18:43.248
She mixed in folk music with jazz.

18:43.333 --> 18:45.542
She played very fine piano.

18:45.627 --> 18:49.087
<i>Her voice was totally different
from anybody else.</i>

18:49.172 --> 18:53.301
<i>It was a woman's voice,
but it had the depth of a baritone.</i>

18:54.219 --> 19:00.141
<i>That depth and that darkness carried
the insight of what was in Nina's soul...</i>

19:01.142 --> 19:03.393
and it reached you very quickly.

19:03.478 --> 19:10.401
<i># For all... #</i>

19:19.077 --> 19:25.081
<i># ...we know #</i>

19:25.166 --> 19:29.044
<i>She was an artist.
She was an original artist.</i>

19:29.129 --> 19:33.298
So we paid attention, and in 1960,
I put her on the Newport Jazz Festival,

19:33.383 --> 19:35.886
<i>and she was a hit there.</i>

19:37.178 --> 19:38.722
[BAND PLAYING]

19:42.726 --> 19:45.268
<i># I got a beau you ain't got none
Little Liza Jane #</i>

19:45.353 --> 19:48.522
<i># I got a beau you ain't got none
Little Liza Jane #</i>

19:48.607 --> 19:51.692
<i># I got a beau you ain't got none
Little Liza Jane #</i>

19:51.777 --> 19:55.028
<i># I got a beau you ain't got none
Little Liza Jane #</i>

19:55.113 --> 19:58.615
<i># Oh, little Liza, little Liza Jane #</i>

19:58.700 --> 20:01.995
<i># Oh, little Liza, little Liza Jane #</i>

20:02.954 --> 20:04.996
STANLEY CROUCH: <i>Her sound is so original.</i>

20:05.081 --> 20:06.623
<i>When she first appeared...</i>

20:06.708 --> 20:09.250
she was one of those musicians who...

20:09.335 --> 20:11.837
Once... You don't have to
hear them a bunch.

20:11.922 --> 20:15.006
If you hear them once,
then the next time you hear 'em, you say,

20:15.091 --> 20:17.050
"Oh, that's that same one
I heard last week.

20:17.135 --> 20:19.510
<i>Nobody sounds like that except her."</i>

20:19.595 --> 20:22.723
<i># Come my love and live with me #</i>

20:22.808 --> 20:26.019
<i># I will take good care of thee,
little Liza Jane #</i>

20:27.228 --> 20:28.228
AL: <i>At Newport,</i>

20:28.313 --> 20:31.189
<i>she was sitting on a high stool
with a tambourine,</i>

20:31.274 --> 20:32.357
<i>and I was in the back.</i>

20:32.442 --> 20:35.360
She wasn't sure
she wanted to go through with it.

20:35.445 --> 20:39.823
<i>If I remember right, she was a little,
you know, "What am I doing here?"</i>

20:39.908 --> 20:42.492
And I said, "You're here because,
you know, you belong here."

20:42.577 --> 20:45.621
<i># He took me to this great big town #</i>

20:45.747 --> 20:48.498
<i># Lot of people standing around #</i>

20:48.583 --> 20:50.333
<i># Little Liza Jane, Jane, Jane... #</i>

20:50.418 --> 20:53.211
And she said,
"Okay, Al, but you better play."

20:53.296 --> 20:56.006
[LAUGHS] And I said,
"Don't worry, I'll play."

20:56.091 --> 20:58.967
<i># Oh little Liza, little Liza Jane #</i>

20:59.052 --> 21:02.472
<i># Oh little Liza, little Liza Jane #</i>

21:03.389 --> 21:06.850
<i>But then, if you watch during
her performance of "Little Liza,"</i>

21:06.935 --> 21:09.062
she has that little smile
from time to time.

21:10.521 --> 21:12.230
<i>She let go, and it was really cute.</i>

21:12.315 --> 21:15.692
<i># Little Liza Jane, Jane
Little ol' Liza #</i>

21:15.777 --> 21:18.569
<i># Little Liza Jane, Jane
Little ol' Liza #</i>

21:18.654 --> 21:22.032
<i># Little Liza Jane, Jane Little ol' Liza #</i>

21:22.117 --> 21:24.492
NINA: <i>Then I recorded seven or eight tunes</i>

21:24.577 --> 21:26.703
<i>that I had been doing all of those years,</i>

21:26.788 --> 21:29.623
<i>and of course, the public
picked out "I Loves You Porgy."</i>

21:29.708 --> 21:33.169
<i>It was not pushed or promoted
to be a hit at all.</i>

21:43.054 --> 21:45.889
- Girls! Guys! Hi.
- Hi, Hugh, nice to see you.

21:45.974 --> 21:46.973
Real good.

21:47.058 --> 21:49.434
Eleanor, you want to, uh,
take Don's coat here,

21:49.519 --> 21:53.021
and maybe you can show the girls
where the powder room is and bedroom.

21:53.106 --> 21:54.605
Hello, there.

21:54.690 --> 21:56.232
Very nice to have you with us
this evening.

21:56.317 --> 21:57.442
This is <i>Playboy's Penthouse,</i>

21:57.527 --> 22:01.197
and I'm Hugh Hefner,
editor/publisher of <i>Playboy</i> magazine.

22:02.407 --> 22:06.492
I'd like you to meet someone that
I think most of you know, Nina Simone.

22:06.577 --> 22:11.164
She came out of nowhere
in the last year as a recording star.

22:11.249 --> 22:13.750
Now has a very, very big record in "Porgy"

22:13.835 --> 22:15.877
that is breaking
all kinds of sales records.

22:15.962 --> 22:17.462
We're very happy she could join us

22:17.547 --> 22:18.964
- tonight on <i>Playboy's Penthouse...</i>
- Thanks.

22:19.049 --> 22:23.593
...and she's going to play and sing
a little bit for us now with her group.

22:23.678 --> 22:25.346
- [ALL CLAPPING]
- [PLAYING PIANO]

22:26.890 --> 22:28.181
Do you want to hear "Porgy"?

22:28.266 --> 22:30.058
- ALL: Very much!
- Right!

22:30.143 --> 22:32.645
Good, that's what we'll do.

22:37.859 --> 22:43.529
<i># I love you, Porgy #</i>

22:43.614 --> 22:47.535
<i># Don't let him take me #</i>

22:49.787 --> 22:52.956
<i># Don't let him handle me #</i>

22:53.041 --> 22:56.920
<i># And drive me mad #</i>

22:58.588 --> 23:01.256
<i># If you can keep me #</i>

23:01.341 --> 23:07.973
<i># I'm gonna stay here with you forever #</i>

23:09.557 --> 23:12.143
<i># And I'll be glad #</i>

23:15.021 --> 23:18.108
<i># Yes, I loves you, Porgy #</i>

23:19.525 --> 23:22.778
<i># Don't let him take me #</i>

23:24.197 --> 23:27.115
<i># Sweetie, don't let him handle me #</i>

23:27.200 --> 23:30.786
<i># With his hot hands #</i>

23:32.914 --> 23:36.207
<i># If you can keep me #</i>

23:36.292 --> 23:42.923
<i># I'm gonna stay here with you forever #</i>

23:43.008 --> 23:46.301
<i># I've got my man #</i>

23:46.386 --> 23:49.137
INTERVIEWER: <i>Nina, there's a man</i>
<i>named Andy Stroud.</i>

23:49.222 --> 23:52.182
<i>He walked into your life
and became a permanent part.</i>

23:52.267 --> 23:53.850
<i>How did you meet your husband?</i>

23:53.935 --> 23:59.772
NINA: <i>He came to see me at a nightclub</i>
<i>and a mutual friend introduced us.</i>

23:59.857 --> 24:04.444
Nina came to the table and sat,
and I was eating a hamburger plate,

24:04.529 --> 24:07.738
and there were fries,
and she dipped into them.

24:07.823 --> 24:10.116
And she wanted to know if it was okay.
I said, "All right."

24:10.201 --> 24:15.413
<i>We got cute and then she gave me
that card with a note on it.</i>

24:15.498 --> 24:19.961
<i>Then I went over to see her at her place
in the next day or two.</i>

24:21.046 --> 24:27.008
<i># But when he comes I know #</i>

24:27.093 --> 24:32.515
<i># I'll have to go #</i>

24:34.309 --> 24:39.312
<i># I love you, Porgy #</i>

24:39.397 --> 24:42.648
INTERVIEWER: <i>How did you know that</i>
<i>Andy Stroud was to be your husband</i>

24:42.733 --> 24:45.693
<i>and not just another guy
out for a date or something else?</i>

24:45.778 --> 24:48.654
[NINA LAUGHS] <i>That's a hard question.</i>

24:48.739 --> 24:52.283
<i>He told me that he had
wanted to meet me for a long time.</i>

24:52.368 --> 24:54.995
<i>And he had come for me.
I fell in love with him.</i>

24:55.080 --> 24:59.916
<i>Then later, he scared me to death.
He was so, you know...</i>

25:00.001 --> 25:03.794
<i>He knew what he wanted
and he just took over.</i>

25:03.879 --> 25:06.506
<i># With you forever #</i>

25:06.591 --> 25:10.176
<i>He abandoned his own career
as a sergeant of the police department</i>

25:10.261 --> 25:11.469
<i>to manage me,</i>

25:11.554 --> 25:15.974
<i>and for the first time, I knew what it was
not to be just floundering out there.</i>

25:16.059 --> 25:19.854
<i># ...got my man #</i>

25:28.238 --> 25:29.905
[SONG ENDS]

25:29.990 --> 25:32.742
[ALL CLAPPING]

25:34.452 --> 25:36.286
AL: <i>I just remember meeting Andy.</i>

25:36.371 --> 25:42.292
Here was a tough, New York,
you know, vice squad cop,

25:42.377 --> 25:47.090
that when he stepped out
of his car uptown, people ran.

25:48.674 --> 25:53.428
And he had... he had a way
of just saying one word...

25:53.513 --> 25:55.180
[IN DEEP VOICE] "Hey."

25:55.265 --> 25:58.516
...and that could put
a lot of fear in people.

25:58.601 --> 26:02.770
<i>But Andy and Nina married in 1961.</i>

26:02.855 --> 26:06.357
<i>He retired from the police force
and became her manager,</i>

26:06.442 --> 26:07.442
<i>and he did well for her.</i>

26:07.527 --> 26:11.029
<i>They bought a beautiful house
in Mount Vernon, New York.</i>

26:11.114 --> 26:15.951
NINA: <i>We had a 13-room house,</i>
<i>four acres of land, lot of trees.</i>

26:16.036 --> 26:19.329
NINA: [SINGING]
<i># My baby don't care for shows #</i>

26:19.414 --> 26:23.209
<i># My baby don't care for clothes #</i>

26:24.794 --> 26:28.339
<i># My baby just cares for me #</i>

26:31.884 --> 26:38.808
<i># My baby don't care for cars and races #</i>

26:40.351 --> 26:42.770
<i># My baby don't care for... #</i>

26:45.731 --> 26:48.566
<i># ...high-tone places #</i>

26:48.651 --> 26:51.361
NINA: <i>And Lisa was born nine months later.</i>

26:51.446 --> 26:57.450
<i>The first three hours after Lisa was born
were the most peaceful in my life,</i>

26:57.535 --> 27:00.203
<i>and I was in love with the world.</i>

27:00.288 --> 27:01.287
<i>And Andrew was there.</i>

27:01.372 --> 27:03.456
<i>He was sitting right there, and he said...</i>

27:03.541 --> 27:05.708
<i>I said, "How's the baby?"
He says, "How's the mother?"</i>

27:05.793 --> 27:07.918
<i>And I loved him for that.</i>

27:08.003 --> 27:09.670
<i>I loved being a mother.</i>

27:09.755 --> 27:11.589
<i>I was a good mother.</i>

27:11.674 --> 27:14.427
<i>I was a goddamn good mother.</i>

27:15.345 --> 27:17.470
LISA: <i>I remember our house in Mount Vernon</i>

27:17.555 --> 27:18.763
<i>like the back of my hand.</i>

27:18.848 --> 27:20.056
<i>It was like a fairy tale.</i>

27:20.141 --> 27:22.808
<i>I remember seeing
the paisley on the walls.</i>

27:22.893 --> 27:25.853
<i>The walls were kind of like a...</i> [SIGHS]

27:25.938 --> 27:28.314
<i>They were hued in gold,
but it really wasn't gold.</i>

27:28.399 --> 27:30.066
<i>It was more like a muted gold</i>

27:30.151 --> 27:31.692
but it felt like it was velvet.

27:31.777 --> 27:36.739
So I'd always run my hands, like,
over the walls, because it was textured.

27:36.824 --> 27:39.242
<i>And my mom, she had her cold storage</i>

27:39.327 --> 27:43.496
<i>where she kept
her fur coats and her costumes.</i>

27:43.581 --> 27:45.208
<i>So I was always in there.</i>

27:45.791 --> 27:47.583
ANDY: <i>These were the good, sweet days.</i>

27:47.668 --> 27:51.256
<i>We were building and growing together.</i>

27:52.089 --> 27:53.883
[SONG CONTINUES]

27:58.846 --> 28:03.891
ANDY: <i>I had an overall plan</i>
<i>to develop and create her as an artist.</i>

28:03.976 --> 28:07.895
I had set up an office
at 5th Avenue and 42nd Street.

28:07.980 --> 28:10.190
<i>I had a publicist.</i>

28:10.275 --> 28:15.195
<i>I had a guy who was a record-promotion man
that I got from Atlantic Records.</i>

28:15.280 --> 28:19.199
<i>I had another fellow who did
the college radio station promotion,</i>

28:19.284 --> 28:22.452
<i>and a photographer.</i>

28:22.537 --> 28:23.953
Dad was the original Puff Daddy.

28:24.038 --> 28:28.624
<i>I mean, he really had a vision,
and he was a very astute businessman.</i>

28:28.709 --> 28:31.877
ANDY: <i>And of course, she was burning</i>
<i>to get on to Carnegie Hall.</i>

28:31.962 --> 28:36.091
<i>She had trained as a classical pianist
with the one thought in mind</i>

28:36.176 --> 28:40.261
of being the first
black female classical pianist

28:40.346 --> 28:42.138
to appear in Carnegie Hall.

28:42.223 --> 28:44.350
That was her prime objective.

28:46.436 --> 28:49.729
<i>However, none of
the New York City promoters</i>

28:49.814 --> 28:52.273
<i>would undertake this project.</i>

28:52.358 --> 28:56.404
<i>So, I took my own money
to promote the appearance.</i>

28:57.655 --> 29:02.493
<i>She was ecstatic. I mean,
she was out of her mind with joy.</i>

29:04.495 --> 29:06.746
INTERVIEWER: <i>You apparently wrote</i>
<i>a letter to your parents saying,</i>

29:06.831 --> 29:09.124
<i>"This is where you wanted me to play,</i>

29:09.209 --> 29:11.542
- <i>but I should have been playing Bach."</i>
- NINA: <i>"Playing Bach."</i>

29:11.627 --> 29:13.211
INTERVIEWER:
<i>So this was your glory occasion,</i>

29:13.296 --> 29:14.795
<i>but you were still disappointed?</i>

29:14.880 --> 29:17.047
NINA: <i>Well, I loved the audience,</i>

29:17.132 --> 29:21.051
<i>but I wasn't playing classical music,
and I wanted to be,</i>

29:21.136 --> 29:22.137
<i>and so I wrote,</i>

29:22.222 --> 29:27.101
<i>"Yes, I'm in Carnegie Hall, finally,
but I'm not playing Bach."</i>

29:29.312 --> 29:30.353
[APPLAUSE]

29:30.438 --> 29:37.362
NINA: [SINGING]
<i># I can't go on without you #</i>

29:40.365 --> 29:47.330
<i># Your love is all I'm living for #</i>

29:49.790 --> 29:56.756
<i># I love all things about you #</i>

29:57.923 --> 30:04.847
<i># Your heart, your soul, my love #</i>

30:08.726 --> 30:10.059
[SONG ENDS]

30:10.144 --> 30:11.729
[APPLAUSE]

30:13.523 --> 30:15.358
[JAZZ PIANO PLAYING]

30:17.735 --> 30:21.111
<i># Say love me, leave me
Let me be lonely #</i>

30:21.196 --> 30:24.073
<i># You won't believe me
but I love you only #</i>

30:24.158 --> 30:25.533
ANDY: <i>After Carnegie Hall,</i>

30:25.618 --> 30:28.536
<i>she was getting airplay
all over the country,</i>

30:28.621 --> 30:31.291
<i>magazine pictures and stories.</i>

30:32.124 --> 30:35.376
<i># Nighttime is my time
for just reminiscing #</i>

30:35.461 --> 30:38.796
<i># Regretting instead of forgetting
with somebody else #</i>

30:38.881 --> 30:42.883
<i>She became highly successful
and recognized.</i>

30:42.968 --> 30:45.303
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

30:45.388 --> 30:47.972
- Oh! Thank you very much!
- MAN: Meeting in Japan.

30:48.057 --> 30:50.641
HOST 1: A young woman who's made
a very emphatic name for herself...

30:50.726 --> 30:52.852
ANNOUNCER: <i>An accomplished pianist</i>
<i>and distinctive...</i>

30:52.937 --> 30:54.437
HOST 2: ...who's now become
a rather famous artist.

30:54.522 --> 30:56.981
HOST 3: A remarkable blues-soul sound.

30:57.066 --> 30:59.024
HOST 4: <i>For the first time
on British television,</i>

30:59.109 --> 31:00.943
<i>The High Priestess of Soul...</i>

31:01.028 --> 31:02.152
[SPEAKING FRENCH]

31:02.237 --> 31:04.154
- Nina Simone.
- Nina Simone.

31:04.239 --> 31:05.325
The great Nina Simone.

31:09.203 --> 31:13.122
HOST 1: <i>Miss Simone brings to her music
a kind of technique and discipline</i>

31:13.207 --> 31:15.458
we generally associate
with classical music.

31:15.543 --> 31:18.127
<i>She has introduced fugue and counterpoint</i>

31:18.212 --> 31:21.757
<i>into the freewheeling spontaneity
of the jazz world.</i>

31:25.678 --> 31:29.847
INTERVIEWER: <i>Nina, do you think that now
that you are successful as a popular artist</i>

31:29.932 --> 31:31.599
<i>that you'd like to do any classical?</i>

31:31.684 --> 31:35.144
NINA: <i>Yes, but I don't have time</i>
<i>to think about it too much.</i>

31:35.229 --> 31:39.649
<i>But you have to realize that when
I'm most satisfied with my music,</i>

31:39.734 --> 31:43.946
<i>I call upon all of the things
that I have learned in classical music.</i>

31:48.576 --> 31:51.952
ANDY: <i>She wanted everything</i>
<i>that money and success could buy.</i>

31:52.037 --> 31:55.956
<i>So I promised her that
she was going to be a rich black bitch.</i>

31:56.041 --> 31:58.668
NINA: <i>We had a blackboard</i>
<i>and he used to put on there,</i>

31:58.753 --> 32:01.629
<i>"I'll be a rich black bitch
by this such-and-such date,"</i>

32:01.714 --> 32:04.424
<i>and he said, "Then you could quit,"
and I always believed him,</i>

32:04.509 --> 32:07.302
<i>but I never could quit
because he worked me too hard.</i>

32:08.554 --> 32:12.598
NINA: [SINGING] <i># Breaking up big rocks</i>
<i>on the chain gang #</i>

32:12.683 --> 32:16.311
<i># Breaking rocks and serving my time #</i>

32:16.396 --> 32:20.230
<i># Breaking up big rocks
on the chain gang #</i>

32:20.315 --> 32:24.109
<i># 'Cause they done convicted me of crime #</i>

32:24.194 --> 32:28.030
<i># Hold it right there while I hit it #</i>

32:28.115 --> 32:31.200
<i># Well, I reckon that ought to get it #</i>

32:31.285 --> 32:34.704
<i># Been workin' and workin' #</i>

32:34.789 --> 32:38.501
<i># But I still got so terribly far to go #</i>

32:39.502 --> 32:43.713
<i># I committed crime Lord, I needed #</i>

32:43.798 --> 32:46.759
<i># Crime of being hungry and poor #</i>

32:47.843 --> 32:51.053
AL: <i>Andy said, "Nina, it's hard work.</i>

32:51.138 --> 32:53.514
<i>You wanna make the money,
you have to work."</i>

32:53.599 --> 32:55.558
<i>And she resented that.</i>

32:55.643 --> 32:56.809
<i>Then Lisa was born,</i>

32:56.894 --> 33:00.771
<i>and she resented being torn away,
having to go on the road.</i>

33:00.856 --> 33:02.565
<i># Well, reckon that ought to get it #</i>

33:02.650 --> 33:05.693
<i># Been working and working... #</i>

33:05.778 --> 33:08.779
LISA: <i>I didn't realize</i>
<i>what my mom did for a living.</i>

33:08.864 --> 33:11.574
<i>I just know that Mom was always traveling.</i>

33:11.659 --> 33:14.994
<i>My mother often told me that
I had 13 nannies in seven years.</i>

33:15.079 --> 33:17.287
<i>So, while she was trying to maintain</i>

33:17.372 --> 33:21.041
some sense of a schedule for me
and normalcy for me,

33:21.126 --> 33:22.627
she was out there doing
what she was doing.

33:22.712 --> 33:25.212
NINA: Can I have five more minutes?
It's very frustrating...

33:25.297 --> 33:28.466
AL: <i>When we were on the road,</i>
<i>there were times we had to be careful.</i>

33:28.551 --> 33:31.552
<i>She could get angry
and start arguments with people.</i>

33:31.637 --> 33:32.845
Y'all pushing! You're pushing!

33:32.930 --> 33:35.348
Don't put nothin' in it!
Let's do it again.

33:35.433 --> 33:38.267
AL: <i>If anyone were talking</i>
<i>in the audience, she would just sit,</i>

33:38.352 --> 33:42.355
and at first, she would say, "Please..."

33:42.440 --> 33:44.982
and she said, "I'm not continuing."

33:45.067 --> 33:48.318
<i>She'd get up, walk out,
and the gig was over.</i>

33:48.403 --> 33:51.947
NINA: <i>I just want them to listen to the
music like they did in the classical world.</i>

33:52.032 --> 33:55.536
<i>I thought they needed teaching.
If they couldn't listen, fuck it!</i>

33:57.455 --> 33:59.121
ANDY: <i>She got into Carnegie Hall,</i>

33:59.206 --> 34:05.461
<i>and she got the big house in the country,
but she began questioning herself.</i>

34:05.546 --> 34:09.674
<i>She'd get into moods of depression
about the whole business,</i>

34:09.759 --> 34:13.135
<i>the personal relationship,
cursing and smashing things,</i>

34:13.219 --> 34:16.514
<i>and this worsened as the time went by.</i>

34:16.599 --> 34:21.185
<i># Gonna see my sweet honey baby #</i>

34:21.270 --> 34:24.938
<i># Gonna break this chain off and run #</i>

34:25.024 --> 34:29.318
<i># I'm gonna lay down somewhere shady #</i>

34:29.402 --> 34:34.449
NINA: <i>All I did was work, work, work.</i>

34:34.534 --> 34:38.828
<i>I was always tired. I was always tired.</i>

34:38.913 --> 34:40.538
<i>I could never sleep.</i>

34:40.623 --> 34:43.373
<i>You see, music always
goes through my head,</i>

34:43.458 --> 34:46.752
<i>which means the more I played,
the less I could relax.</i>

34:46.837 --> 34:49.254
<i>I kept thinking Andy would let me rest.</i>

34:49.339 --> 34:50.965
<i>He never did.</i>

34:51.050 --> 34:54.635
<i># But I still... #</i>

34:54.719 --> 35:00.601
<i># ...got so terribly far to go #</i>

35:04.271 --> 35:06.356
- [SONG ENDS]
- [APPLAUSE]

35:15.741 --> 35:18.493
<i># Got my liver #</i>

35:21.163 --> 35:24.665
AL: <i>She felt she was being</i>
<i>handled like a racehorse,</i>

35:24.750 --> 35:27.460
and she was always
fighting, fighting, fighting it.

35:27.545 --> 35:30.921
<i>Andy would say,
"Nina, we've got a career here.</i>

35:31.006 --> 35:34.174
<i>That's not going to continue
if you don't nurture it."</i>

35:34.259 --> 35:38.012
<i>So, she came to resent Andy...</i>

35:38.097 --> 35:39.724
but she was afraid of Andy.

35:41.100 --> 35:44.935
NINA: <i>Andrew protected me</i>
<i>against everybody but himself.</i>

35:45.020 --> 35:47.772
<i>He wrapped himself around me like a snake.</i>

35:47.857 --> 35:51.358
<i>I worked like a dog,
and I was scared of him...</i>

35:51.443 --> 35:53.486
<i>and Andrew beat me up.</i>

35:53.571 --> 35:55.988
<i>But I've never talked to you about this.</i>

35:56.073 --> 35:59.284
<i>But he beat me up.
I was deathly scared of Andrew.</i>

36:01.704 --> 36:03.706
<i># I put a spell on you #</i>

36:09.003 --> 36:11.631
<i># 'Cause you're mine #</i>

36:13.548 --> 36:18.636
One time, early in the morning,
like 4:00, 5:00 in the morning, uh...

36:18.721 --> 36:23.976
the phone rings. It's Nina,
and she needed to hide out.

36:25.269 --> 36:26.894
<i># I ain't lying #</i>

36:26.979 --> 36:31.315
NINA: <i>I had gone</i>
<i>to a discotheque with Andrew...</i>

36:31.400 --> 36:33.984
<i>and a fan came up to me
and gave me a note,</i>

36:34.069 --> 36:37.655
<i>and he saw me take this note
and put it in my pocket.</i>

36:37.740 --> 36:41.116
<i># You're runnin' around
You know better, Daddy #</i>

36:41.201 --> 36:44.244
AL: <i>She thought nothing of it.</i>
<i>I mean, she related this to me.</i>

36:44.329 --> 36:46.706
<i>And Andy came back and grabbed her arm</i>

36:46.791 --> 36:50.668
and took her out from the place
and beat her up.

36:50.753 --> 36:54.922
NINA: <i>And when I got out on the street,</i>
<i>he started raining blows on me.</i>

36:55.007 --> 36:56.256
<i>Bloody blows.</i>

36:56.341 --> 36:58.884
<i>He beat me all the way home,</i>

36:58.969 --> 37:04.599
<i>up the stairs, in the elevator,
in my room, put a gun to my head.</i>

37:04.684 --> 37:06.977
<i>Then he tied me up and raped me.</i>

37:10.981 --> 37:15.568
She came to my place and...
and she was beat up.

37:15.653 --> 37:18.445
And I, you know, put her to bed, and...

37:18.530 --> 37:23.117
and she, you know,
rested for a couple of days.

37:23.202 --> 37:25.410
NINA: <i>He didn't find me for two weeks.</i>

37:25.495 --> 37:27.496
<i>My eyes, I couldn't see.</i>

37:27.581 --> 37:30.165
<i>And he said, "Who beat you up like that?"</i>

37:30.250 --> 37:31.250
<i>And I said, "You did!"</i>

37:31.335 --> 37:33.794
<i>He said, "No, I didn't.
I've been looking for you for two weeks."</i>

37:33.879 --> 37:36.505
<i>I said, "You're insane!"</i>

37:36.590 --> 37:40.134
<i>He was brutal... but I... I loved him</i>

37:40.219 --> 37:43.638
<i>and I guess I just believed
he wouldn't do it anymore.</i>

37:43.723 --> 37:46.558
<i># You're mine #</i>

37:54.399 --> 37:57.567
LISA: <i>My mother always said,</i>
<i>till the day she died,</i>

37:57.652 --> 38:00.863
<i>Dad was the best manager
that she ever had.</i>

38:00.948 --> 38:02.948
<i>But on top of being charismatic,</i>

38:03.033 --> 38:07.369
<i>he could be a bully
and he could be very mean,</i>

38:07.454 --> 38:11.707
and she was on
the receiving end of that...

38:11.792 --> 38:15.711
more times than, you know,
she should have been,

38:15.796 --> 38:17.131
which should have been never.

38:18.215 --> 38:20.716
<i>Mom would allude to, you know,</i>

38:20.801 --> 38:24.136
<i>"He's rammed my head
into a concrete wall."</i>

38:24.221 --> 38:26.346
<i>She said that
he punched her in the stomach</i>

38:26.431 --> 38:27.975
<i>when she was pregnant with me.</i>

38:44.074 --> 38:47.576
LISA: <i>As a child, I remember</i>
<i>sitting in the car between them</i>

38:47.661 --> 38:49.787
<i>and they were arguing about something,</i>

38:49.872 --> 38:53.457
and I remember my father
reaching across me,

38:53.542 --> 38:55.920
so it was like this, and backhanding her.

38:57.296 --> 39:01.757
ANDY: <i>We're going home in the car,</i>
<i>I'm driving, and I slapped her.</i>

39:01.842 --> 39:06.178
<i>Blood spurted... right over this eyebrow.</i>

39:06.263 --> 39:11.183
<i>She had, like, a one-inch cut
from my ring, you know.</i>

39:11.268 --> 39:12.559
<i>We got her home</i>

39:12.644 --> 39:17.272
<i>and I clipped the skin together
and taped it...</i>

39:17.357 --> 39:20.820
<i>and a week later,
there wasn't even a scar.</i>

39:23.155 --> 39:24.822
LISA: <i>I think they were both nuts.</i>

39:24.907 --> 39:27.282
<i>She stayed with him.</i>

39:27.367 --> 39:29.286
<i>She had this love affair with fire.</i>

39:32.247 --> 39:35.040
That's like inviting the bull
with the red cape,

39:35.125 --> 39:37.877
"Just come on into my kitchen
and let's see what we can do."

39:37.962 --> 39:39.920
That's what she did.

39:40.005 --> 39:42.297
- What do I want for her?
- INTERVIEWER: Yes.

39:42.382 --> 39:44.925
Myself. What else?

39:45.010 --> 39:46.761
- [LAUGHING]
- INTERVIEWER: Career-wise.

39:48.263 --> 39:51.598
LISA: <i>My father had</i>
<i>a strategic plan in terms of</i>

39:51.683 --> 39:54.101
<i>how Mom's career was going to go.</i>

39:54.186 --> 39:57.479
<i>He wanted her to be able
to win all the awards,</i>

39:57.564 --> 40:01.110
<i>and to become the huge star
that he knew that she could be...</i>

40:02.862 --> 40:05.320
but she wanted something more.

40:05.405 --> 40:09.199
There was something missing in her,
some meaning.

40:09.284 --> 40:10.870
- [BOOMING]
- [GLASS SHATTERING]

40:14.623 --> 40:18.667
NEWSCASTER 1: <i>They died in Birmingham,</i>
<i>the nation's most segregated big city.</i>

40:18.752 --> 40:20.377
<i>Dynamite exploded on Sunday morning,</i>

40:20.462 --> 40:23.630
<i>killed four little girls,
injured 20 other Negroes.</i>

40:23.715 --> 40:26.633
NEWSCASTER 2: <i>It was one of more
than 40 bombings in that Birmingham area.</i>

40:26.718 --> 40:28.010
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

40:28.095 --> 40:34.183
JAMES BALDWIN: <i>Kids were murdered</i>
<i>in Birmingham on a Sunday</i>

40:34.268 --> 40:37.102
and in Sunday schools
in a Christian nation,

40:37.187 --> 40:38.355
- and nobody cares!
- [BANGS PODIUM]

40:39.857 --> 40:44.734
NINA: <i>When the kids got killed</i>
<i>in that church... that did it.</i>

40:44.819 --> 40:47.281
<i>First you get depressed,
and after that, you get mad.</i>

40:48.198 --> 40:50.324
<i>And when these kids got bombed,</i>

40:50.409 --> 40:52.659
I just sat down and wrote this song.

40:52.744 --> 40:56.413
And it's a very... moving, violent song,

40:56.498 --> 40:58.498
'cause that's how I feel
about the whole thing.

40:58.583 --> 41:03.921
<i># Alabama's gotten me so upset
Tennessee made me lose my rest #</i>

41:04.006 --> 41:09.093
<i># Everybody knows about Mississippi,
goddam #</i>

41:09.178 --> 41:12.930
<i># Can't you see it?
I know you can feel it #</i>

41:13.015 --> 41:15.265
<i># It's all in the air #</i>

41:15.350 --> 41:18.602
<i># I can't stand this pressure
much longer #</i>

41:18.687 --> 41:21.521
<i># Somebody say a prayer #</i>

41:21.606 --> 41:27.069
<i># Alabama's gotten me so upset
And Tennessee's made me lose my rest #</i>

41:27.154 --> 41:31.866
<i># Everybody knows about Mississippi,
goddam #</i>

41:34.078 --> 41:35.285
DICK GREGORY: <i>"Mississippi Goddam."</i>

41:35.370 --> 41:36.536
Phew!

41:36.621 --> 41:38.330
Hmm? Got my attention.

41:38.415 --> 41:41.416
<i>What she was doing was different.</i>

41:41.501 --> 41:45.545
There's something about a woman...

41:45.630 --> 41:49.799
if you look at all the suffering
that black folks went through...

41:49.884 --> 41:55.180
not one black man would dare say,
"Mississippi, goddam."

41:55.265 --> 42:01.020
<i>And then to have someone with her stature
talking about your problem,</i>

42:01.105 --> 42:03.272
<i>you know how happy they had to be?</i>

42:03.357 --> 42:06.235
<i>We all wanted to say it. She said it.</i>

42:07.402 --> 42:09.111
"Mississippi, goddam!"

42:09.196 --> 42:12.406
<i># Hound dogs on my trail #</i>

42:12.491 --> 42:15.409
<i># School children sitting in jail #</i>

42:15.494 --> 42:17.536
<i># Black cat cross my path #</i>

42:17.621 --> 42:21.206
<i># I think every day's gonna be my last #</i>

42:21.291 --> 42:24.834
<i># Oh, but my country is full of lies #</i>

42:24.919 --> 42:27.754
<i># We all gonna die and die like flies #</i>

42:27.839 --> 42:30.215
<i># I don't trust nobody any more #</i>

42:30.300 --> 42:34.386
<i># They keep on saying, "Go slow" #</i>

42:34.471 --> 42:36.763
LISA: <i>For Mommy to write a song</i>
<i>called "Mississippi Goddam"</i>

42:36.848 --> 42:38.015
<i>was revolutionary.</i>

42:38.100 --> 42:41.435
<i>They didn't have cursing on the radio
or on television or anything.</i>

42:41.520 --> 42:42.978
<i>DJs refused to play it,</i>

42:43.063 --> 42:48.275
and boxes of the 45s used to be sent back
from the radio stations cracked in two.

42:48.360 --> 42:51.611
- <i># Well, that's just the trouble #</i>
- [CHORUS] <i># Too slow #</i>

42:51.696 --> 42:54.656
- <i># Washing the windows #</i>
- <i># Too slow #</i>

42:54.741 --> 42:57.451
- <i># Pickin' the cotton #</i>
- <i># Too slow #</i>

42:57.536 --> 43:00.287
- <i># We're nothin' but rotten #</i>
- <i># Too slow #</i>

43:00.372 --> 43:02.998
- <i># We're too damn lazy #</i>
- <i># Too slow #</i>

43:03.083 --> 43:06.085
- <i># Our thinkin' is crazy #</i>
- <i># Too slow #</i>

43:06.170 --> 43:08.963
<i># Where am I going?
Or what am I doing? #</i>

43:09.048 --> 43:11.840
<i># I don't know, I don't know #</i>

43:11.925 --> 43:14.884
AL: <i>As the civil rights movement</i>
<i>really swung into high gear,</i>

43:14.969 --> 43:17.221
she swung into high gear with it.

43:17.306 --> 43:22.684
<i>In '65, we played at the Selma March
in Montgomery, Alabama.</i>

43:22.769 --> 43:26.813
MARTIN LUTHER KING JR.:
<i>We have a legal and constitutional right</i>

43:26.898 --> 43:30.359
- to march from Selma to Montgomery!
- [CROWD CHEERING]

43:30.444 --> 43:32.945
AL: <i>It was extremely dangerous.</i>

43:33.030 --> 43:35.197
<i>The federal Marshals were called in,</i>

43:35.282 --> 43:38.951
<i>and they were standing
on the tops of all the buildings downtown</i>

43:39.036 --> 43:41.286
<i>with guns.</i>

43:41.371 --> 43:44.873
ANDY: <i>Seated in front of the stage</i>
<i>facing the audience</i>

43:44.958 --> 43:46.416
<i>was Martin Luther King,</i>

43:46.501 --> 43:50.837
<i>Ralph Bunche from the UN
and a lot of other worldwide dignitaries.</i>

43:50.922 --> 43:55.300
AL: <i>You had Langston Hughes,</i>
<i>James Baldwin, Sidney Poitier,</i>

43:55.385 --> 43:58.512
<i>Bill Cosby, Leonard Bernstein,
Harry Belafonte,</i>

43:58.597 --> 44:00.514
and we did "Mississippi Goddam."

44:00.599 --> 44:03.810
<i># Can't you see it?
Can't you feel it? #</i>

44:05.354 --> 44:07.812
<i># It's all in the air #</i>

44:07.897 --> 44:11.816
<i># I can't stand the pressure much longer #</i>

44:11.901 --> 44:13.987
<i># Somebody say a prayer #</i>

44:15.489 --> 44:18.740
<i># Alabama's got me so upset #</i>

44:18.825 --> 44:21.535
<i># Selma made me lose my rest #</i>

44:21.620 --> 44:23.578
[CROWD CHEERING]

44:23.663 --> 44:27.501
<i># Everybody knows
about Mississippi, goddam #</i>

44:31.088 --> 44:33.672
LISA: <i>My mother said that
after she sang that song,</i>

44:33.757 --> 44:37.592
<i>she got so angry that her voice broke...</i>

44:37.677 --> 44:39.428
<i>and from "Mississippi Goddam" on,</i>

44:39.513 --> 44:43.932
it never, ever returned
to its former octave.

44:44.017 --> 44:46.351
[CROWD SINGING
"GO TELL IT ON THE MOUNTAIN"]

44:46.436 --> 44:50.857
<i>But I think that Mom's anger
is what sustained her.</i>

44:51.858 --> 44:56.820
<i>The energy and the creativity
and the passion of those days</i>

44:56.905 --> 44:58.573
<i>is really what kept her going.</i>

45:14.088 --> 45:15.755
ANDY: <i>When she wrote "Mississippi Goddam,"</i>

45:15.840 --> 45:17.341
<i>I thought it was something else.</i>

45:17.426 --> 45:19.343
<i>You know, I liked it.</i>

45:19.428 --> 45:22.472
<i>They put a 45 out on it,
and I knew it had a lot of impact.</i>

45:23.182 --> 45:25.640
<i>But my complaint was that</i>

45:25.725 --> 45:29.728
while I was always pushing
for the commercial side of the picture,

45:29.813 --> 45:34.067
<i>she got sidetracked with
all of these civil rights activities.</i>

45:35.319 --> 45:38.320
NINA: <i>When the civil rights thing
came up, all of a sudden,</i>

45:38.405 --> 45:44.075
<i>I could let myself be heard
about what I'd been feeling all the time.</i>

45:44.160 --> 45:47.496
<i>When I was young, I knew to stay alive.</i>

45:47.581 --> 45:50.499
<i>As a black family, we had to work at it.</i>

45:50.584 --> 45:52.792
<i>We had to keep secrets.</i>

45:52.877 --> 45:55.920
<i>We never complained about being poor,</i>

45:56.005 --> 45:59.341
<i>or being taken advantage of
or not getting our share.</i>

45:59.426 --> 46:01.843
<i>We had to keep our mouths shut</i>

46:01.928 --> 46:05.139
<i>as I walked across
that railroad track every Saturday.</i>

46:05.224 --> 46:08.057
<i>So I knew to break the silence</i>

46:08.142 --> 46:12.606
<i>meant a confrontation
with the white people of that town.</i>

46:14.023 --> 46:15.399
NINA: [SINGING] <i># Southern trees #</i>

46:15.484 --> 46:17.317
<i>And though I didn't know I knew it,</i>

46:17.402 --> 46:20.945
<i>if the black man rises up and says,
"I'm just not gonna do that anymore..."</i>

46:21.030 --> 46:24.699
<i># Bearin' strange fruit #</i>

46:24.784 --> 46:27.161
<i>...he stands to get murdered.</i>

46:28.372 --> 46:30.914
<i># Blood on the leaves #</i>

46:30.999 --> 46:34.918
<i>But no one mentioned that,
which is, indeed, quite strange.</i>

46:35.003 --> 46:38.006
<i># And blood at the roots #</i>

46:42.511 --> 46:48.224
<i># Black bodies swinging
in the southern breeze #</i>

46:53.229 --> 46:56.898
NINA: <i>It touched me first time</i>
<i>when I gave a recital at this library.</i>

46:56.983 --> 46:59.234
<i>Everybody was seated</i>

46:59.319 --> 47:01.861
<i>and they told me
my parents had to sit in the back,</i>

47:01.946 --> 47:02.946
<i>and I said,</i>

47:03.031 --> 47:05.615
<i>"If they have to sit in the back,
I won't perform."</i>

47:05.700 --> 47:07.075
<i>They fixed it that time</i>

47:07.160 --> 47:09.661
<i>and they brought them to the front
and they let them sit down,</i>

47:09.746 --> 47:14.874
<i>but it was my first feeling
of being discriminated against,</i>

47:14.959 --> 47:18.380
<i>and I recoiled in horror at such a thing.</i>

47:23.593 --> 47:26.386
[PEOPLE CLAMORING]

47:26.471 --> 47:28.181
[PLAYING "THE BACKLASH BLUES"]

47:38.024 --> 47:39.693
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

47:47.742 --> 47:50.785
<i># Mr. Backlash #</i>

47:50.870 --> 47:52.789
<i># Who do you think I am? #</i>

47:54.583 --> 47:59.629
<i># You raise my taxes and freeze my wages
Send my only son to Vietnam #</i>

48:01.381 --> 48:03.675
<i># You give me second class houses #</i>

48:04.718 --> 48:06.720
<i># You give me second class schools #</i>

48:07.929 --> 48:12.726
<i># You think all colored people
are just second class fools #</i>

48:14.060 --> 48:16.813
<i># Mr. Backlash #</i>

48:17.814 --> 48:21.526
<i># I'm gonna leave you with the blues
Yes, I am #</i>

48:27.949 --> 48:33.287
I choose to reflect the times
and the situations in which I find myself.

48:33.372 --> 48:35.789
That, to me, is my duty...

48:35.874 --> 48:38.583
and at this crucial time in our lives,

48:38.668 --> 48:43.171
when everything is so desperate,
when every day is a matter of survival,

48:43.256 --> 48:45.507
I don't think you can help
but be involved.

48:45.592 --> 48:47.301
Young people, black and white, know this,

48:47.386 --> 48:50.011
and so that's why
they're so involved in politics.

48:50.096 --> 48:52.013
We will shape and mold this country

48:52.098 --> 48:55.141
or it will not be molded and shaped
at all anymore.

48:55.226 --> 48:56.643
So I don't think you have a choice...

48:56.728 --> 49:00.148
How can you be an artist
and not reflect the times?

49:00.857 --> 49:03.026
<i># When I try to find a job #</i>

49:04.444 --> 49:06.237
<i># To earn a little cash #</i>

49:07.656 --> 49:11.908
<i># All you got to offer
Is your mean old white backlash #</i>

49:11.993 --> 49:13.578
<i># But the world is big #</i>

49:17.373 --> 49:19.250
<i># Big and bright and round #</i>

49:21.044 --> 49:25.129
<i># And it's full of other folks like me
Who are black, yellow, beige and brown #</i>

49:25.214 --> 49:26.466
<i># You better believe me #</i>

49:27.926 --> 49:30.679
<i># Mr. Backlash #</i>

49:31.680 --> 49:34.307
<i># I'm gonna leave you with the blues #</i>

49:42.774 --> 49:44.858
NINA: <i>I've always thought that</i>
<i>I was shaking people up,</i>

49:44.943 --> 49:47.361
but now I want to go at it more

49:47.446 --> 49:51.322
and I want to go at it more deliberately
and I want to go at it coldly.

49:51.407 --> 49:54.409
I want... I want to shake people up so bad

49:54.494 --> 49:58.580
that when they leave a nightclub
where I've performed,

49:58.665 --> 50:00.707
I just want them to be to pieces.

50:00.792 --> 50:03.084
All right!

50:03.169 --> 50:04.838
["BACKLASH BLUES" PLAYING]

50:35.409 --> 50:37.911
<i># I said, when he died #</i>

50:37.996 --> 50:39.621
<i># I said, when he died #</i>

50:39.706 --> 50:42.416
<i># He told me all my life #</i>

50:42.501 --> 50:45.251
<i># He said, "Keep on working girl #</i>

50:45.336 --> 50:49.633
<i># They open up the door
one of these days #</i>

50:50.466 --> 50:53.052
<i># You won't have to wait much longer #</i>

50:54.387 --> 50:58.347
<i># Just tell 'em exactly how you feel #</i>

50:58.432 --> 51:02.226
<i># So I'm gonna leave you with the blues #</i>

51:02.311 --> 51:04.939
<i># That's me, yeah" #</i>

51:06.566 --> 51:08.817
I want to go in that den

51:08.902 --> 51:13.447
of those elegant people
with their old ideas, smugness,

51:13.532 --> 51:15.323
and just drive them insane.

51:15.408 --> 51:16.910
NINA: Rise up!

51:20.246 --> 51:21.915
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

51:35.469 --> 51:37.847
It's all right if you dance slow!

51:45.188 --> 51:48.607
<i>But it was very exhilarating
to be part of that movement at the time</i>

51:48.692 --> 51:50.399
<i>because I was needed.</i>

51:50.484 --> 51:56.239
<i>Now I could sing to help my people,
and that became the mainstay of my life.</i>

51:56.324 --> 52:01.661
<i>Not classical piano, not classical music,
not even popular music,</i>

52:01.746 --> 52:04.247
<i>but civil rights music.</i>

52:04.332 --> 52:09.293
<i>I got to know Martin Luther King,
Malcolm X, Andrew Young,</i>

52:09.378 --> 52:12.964
<i>and artists, actors,
actresses, poets, writers,</i>

52:13.049 --> 52:17.426
<i>people like myself who felt compelled
to make the stand that I have.</i>

52:17.511 --> 52:21.222
ROGER: <i>It was very important</i>
<i>for her to connect with</i>

52:21.307 --> 52:24.183
<i>the writers and playwrights of that moment</i>

52:24.268 --> 52:25.977
<i>because those people had</i>

52:26.062 --> 52:29.230
<i>the intellectual background
of the movement</i>

52:29.315 --> 52:30.774
and she didn't have that.

52:30.859 --> 52:32.861
She had music, the musical background.

52:33.527 --> 52:35.153
<i>For instance, Langston Hughes,</i>

52:35.238 --> 52:37.822
<i>he wrote the lyrics
for "Backlash Blues" for her.</i>

52:37.907 --> 52:42.118
<i>Lorraine Hansberry, Nina took her play,</i>
Young, Gifted, and Black,

52:42.203 --> 52:43.662
<i>and made a song out of it.</i>

52:43.747 --> 52:44.746
It's regarded as

52:44.831 --> 52:47.333
one of the most important songs
in the civil rights movement.

52:48.334 --> 52:51.502
NINA: I know that there are only
300 black students here

52:51.587 --> 52:54.839
in this college of 18,000.

52:54.924 --> 52:58.344
So this song is dedicated only to you.

52:59.012 --> 53:03.182
<i># To be young, gifted and black #</i>

53:04.267 --> 53:10.314
<i># Oh, what a lovely, precious dream #</i>

53:11.440 --> 53:16.069
<i># To be young, gifted and black #</i>

53:16.154 --> 53:18.446
NINA:
<i>Lorraine Hansberry was my best friend,</i>

53:18.531 --> 53:22.408
<i>and she wrote plays,</i> Raisin in the Sun
<i>and</i> Young, Gifted, and Black.

53:22.493 --> 53:25.912
<i>She taught me a lot about
Karl Marx, Lenin, philosophy.</i>

53:25.997 --> 53:28.206
[LORRAINE HANSBERRY]
<i>The basic fabric of our society</i>

53:28.291 --> 53:30.667
<i>that has Negroes
in the situation that they are in</i>

53:30.752 --> 53:33.713
<i>is the thing which must
be changed, you know.</i>

53:35.256 --> 53:39.843
<i># Who are young, gifted and black #</i>

53:39.928 --> 53:42.762
LISA: <i>Those times were pretty amazing.</i>

53:42.847 --> 53:46.224
I look back now and I'm just like,
"Wow! Who's who of Black America!"

53:46.309 --> 53:48.101
Lorraine Hansberry was my godmother.

53:48.186 --> 53:52.313
<i>Malcolm X's wife,
Betty Shabazz, was my auntie.</i>

53:52.398 --> 53:54.858
<i>They lived right next door
in Mount Vernon.</i>

53:54.943 --> 53:56.860
<i>There are six daughters
and I was like the seventh.</i>

53:56.945 --> 53:59.362
<i>So I was always riding my bike over there.</i>

53:59.447 --> 54:02.490
Lisa and I were the same age, and...

54:02.575 --> 54:05.034
I think we may have
called one another twins.

54:05.119 --> 54:07.746
<i>It was just a great, great time.</i>

54:07.831 --> 54:10.123
<i>There was music, there were discussions.</i>

54:10.208 --> 54:14.711
<i>Whether it was at our house
or Lisa's house, Nina Simone's home,</i>

54:14.796 --> 54:17.841
it was definitely party with a purpose.

54:18.466 --> 54:20.884
[AMBASSADOR SHABAZZ]
<i>We happened to be a fly on the wall</i>

54:20.969 --> 54:27.932
with some of the genius
poets and poetesses of the time, the era.

54:28.017 --> 54:30.810
<i>And to sit in that room and listen...</i>

54:30.895 --> 54:34.648
These were brilliant,
well-read, well-traveled,

54:34.733 --> 54:39.193
<i>charming, alluring, charismatic people</i>

54:39.278 --> 54:42.323
<i>who were moved
to make a difference in the world.</i>

54:42.949 --> 54:46.534
<i>I'm born of the</i>
Young, Gifted, and Black <i>affirmation.</i>

54:46.619 --> 54:50.163
<i>For me, and those of us
in that environment,</i>

54:50.248 --> 54:53.416
it was daring to proclaim it...

54:53.501 --> 54:57.461
and then share it joyously
when she sang it.

54:57.546 --> 55:02.175
<i># To be young, gifted and black #</i>

55:02.260 --> 55:06.512
SHABAZZ: <i>People would stand up</i>
<i>and engage in their African-ness</i>

55:06.597 --> 55:08.682
<i>without apology...</i>

55:08.767 --> 55:12.351
and it's a contemporary,
hip song of the era.

55:12.436 --> 55:15.313
It means you get to hum it in public.
[LAUGHS]

55:15.398 --> 55:18.149
<i># It's where it's at #</i>

55:18.234 --> 55:19.443
[CROWD CHEERING]

55:20.444 --> 55:23.905
ANDY: <i>She became a legend</i>
<i>in the activists' movement,</i>

55:23.990 --> 55:27.575
<i>and through meetings
and discussions that I overheard,</i>

55:27.660 --> 55:31.120
<i>she was convinced that
certain things must be done</i>

55:31.205 --> 55:34.498
in order to... push the revolution.

55:34.583 --> 55:37.335
<i>I told them that's not the answer,</i>

55:37.420 --> 55:42.631
and then it began to manifest in
her attitude towards me and the business.

55:42.716 --> 55:44.383
She'd fly off.

55:44.468 --> 55:45.969
I remember a few nights, you know,

55:46.054 --> 55:48.596
you go to bed happy
and holding one another.

55:48.681 --> 55:49.680
I wake up,

55:49.765 --> 55:52.558
and she'd be sitting up in bed
with her arms folded,

55:52.643 --> 55:54.562
looking at me, thinking about killing me.

55:55.229 --> 56:00.484
<i>And this is how it went.
The political work became very heavy.</i>

56:01.820 --> 56:03.862
NINA: <i>To me, we are the most</i>
<i>beautiful creatures</i>

56:03.947 --> 56:06.155
<i>in the whole world, black people.</i>

56:06.240 --> 56:10.701
<i>So my job is to make them more curious</i>

56:10.786 --> 56:13.079
about where they came from

56:13.164 --> 56:17.792
and their own identity
and pride in that identity.

56:17.877 --> 56:19.168
That's why my songs...

56:19.253 --> 56:21.838
I try to make them
as powerful as possible,

56:21.923 --> 56:25.299
mostly just to make them
curious about themselves.

56:25.384 --> 56:26.968
We don't know anything about ourselves.

56:27.053 --> 56:28.052
We don't even have

56:28.137 --> 56:30.930
the pride and the dignity
of African people,

56:31.015 --> 56:33.892
but we can't even talk about
where we came from.

56:33.977 --> 56:35.601
We don't know.

56:35.686 --> 56:37.813
It's like a lost race.

56:38.439 --> 56:40.940
<i># Ain't got no home #</i>

56:41.025 --> 56:43.860
<i># Ain't got no shoes #</i>

56:43.945 --> 56:46.237
<i># Ain't got no money #</i>

56:46.322 --> 56:48.823
<i># Ain't got no class #</i>

56:48.908 --> 56:51.450
<i># Ain't got no skirts #</i>

56:51.535 --> 56:54.037
<i># Ain't got no sweaters #</i>

56:54.122 --> 56:56.622
<i># Ain't got no perfume #</i>

56:56.707 --> 56:59.250
<i># Ain't got no love #</i>

56:59.335 --> 57:01.420
<i># Ain't got no faith #</i>

57:04.257 --> 57:06.925
<i># I ain't got no culture #</i>

57:07.010 --> 57:09.468
<i># Ain't got no mother #</i>

57:09.553 --> 57:12.013
<i># Ain't got no father #</i>

57:12.098 --> 57:14.598
<i># Ain't got no brother #</i>

57:14.683 --> 57:16.810
<i># Ain't got no children #</i>

57:17.270 --> 57:19.728
<i># Ain't got no aunts #</i>

57:19.813 --> 57:22.273
<i># Ain't got no uncles #</i>

57:22.358 --> 57:24.776
<i># Ain't got no love #</i>

57:24.861 --> 57:26.612
<i># Ain't got no mind #</i>

57:29.866 --> 57:32.408
<i># I ain't got no country #</i>

57:32.493 --> 57:34.953
<i># Ain't got no schoolin' #</i>

57:35.038 --> 57:37.496
<i># Ain't got no friends #</i>

57:37.581 --> 57:40.416
<i># Ain't got no nothin' #</i>

57:40.501 --> 57:42.501
<i># Ain't got no wine #</i>

57:42.586 --> 57:44.921
<i># Ain't got no money #</i>

57:45.006 --> 57:47.423
<i># Ain't got no faith #</i>

57:47.508 --> 57:49.843
<i># Ain't got no God #</i>

57:49.928 --> 57:52.889
<i># Ain't got no love #</i>

57:54.848 --> 57:57.143
<i># Then what have I got? #</i>

57:57.726 --> 58:03.522
I really mean to provoke this feeling of,
like, "Who am I? Where'd I come from?"

58:03.607 --> 58:06.192
You know, "Do I really like me?"
and, "Why do I like me?"

58:06.277 --> 58:09.278
And, like, you know,
"If I am black and beautiful,

58:09.363 --> 58:12.741
I really am and I know it,
and I don't care who cares or says what."

58:13.867 --> 58:16.535
<i># I got my hair, got my head #</i>

58:16.620 --> 58:18.913
<i># Got my brains, got my ears #</i>

58:18.998 --> 58:23.334
<i># Got my eyes, got my nose Got my mouth #</i>

58:23.419 --> 58:26.047
<i># I got my sex #</i>

58:28.007 --> 58:30.591
<i># I got my arms, got my hands #</i>

58:30.676 --> 58:33.136
<i># Got my fingers, got my legs #</i>

58:33.221 --> 58:35.554
<i># Got my feet, got my toes #</i>

58:35.639 --> 58:37.640
<i># Got my liver #</i>

58:37.725 --> 58:40.018
<i># Got my blood #</i>

58:40.103 --> 58:41.645
<i># I've got life #</i>

58:44.607 --> 58:46.900
<i># I've got life #</i>

58:49.112 --> 58:52.155
<i># I've got headaches and toothaches #</i>

58:52.240 --> 58:57.245
<i># And bad times, too, like you #</i>

58:58.371 --> 59:01.122
<i># I got my hair, got my head #</i>

59:01.207 --> 59:03.291
<i># Got my brains, got my ears #</i>

59:03.376 --> 59:05.459
<i># Got my eyes, got my nose #</i>

59:05.544 --> 59:07.586
NINA: <i>This is what compels me</i>

59:07.671 --> 59:11.382
<i>to push black people
to identify with black culture.</i>

59:11.467 --> 59:16.889
Giving out to them that black-ness,
that black power.

59:17.556 --> 59:19.723
<i># Got my heart, got my soul #</i>

59:19.808 --> 59:21.684
<i># Got my back #</i>

59:21.769 --> 59:24.272
<i># I got my sex #</i>

59:26.690 --> 59:28.649
STANLEY CROUCH: <i>Nina was a real rebel.</i>

59:28.734 --> 59:30.151
<i>She didn't really fit</i>

59:30.236 --> 59:34.032
in the revolutionary black female role
that was offered her.

59:34.782 --> 59:38.034
<i>She could avoid pretentious phoniness</i>

59:38.119 --> 59:40.536
<i>and get more depth out of a song</i>

59:40.621 --> 59:43.331
<i>than people are used to hearing
out of those songs.</i>

59:43.416 --> 59:45.084
<i># I got my freedom #</i>

59:46.710 --> 59:50.631
She was a kind of patron saint
of the rebellion.

59:53.551 --> 59:55.051
[SONG ENDS]

59:55.136 --> 59:56.845
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

01:00:01.434 --> 01:00:04.352
AL: <i>Nina started to get more aggressive.</i>

01:00:04.437 --> 01:00:07.940
<i>I remember one time as she
walked right up to Dr. King and said,</i>

01:00:08.607 --> 01:00:11.317
"I'm not non-violent!"

01:00:11.402 --> 01:00:15.529
And he said, "That's okay, sister.
You don't have to be."

01:00:15.614 --> 01:00:19.242
NINA: <i>I was never non-violent. Never.</i>

01:00:19.327 --> 01:00:23.162
<i>I thought we should get our rights
by any means necessary.</i>

01:00:23.247 --> 01:00:25.664
AL: <i>And then she met Stokely Carmichael.</i>

01:00:25.749 --> 01:00:28.584
Miss Simone says
something very significant

01:00:28.669 --> 01:00:30.836
in her song "Mississippi Goddam."

01:00:30.921 --> 01:00:35.841
She says, "This country..."
She says, "This country is built on lies."

01:00:35.926 --> 01:00:38.511
You're gonna sit in front
of your television set

01:00:38.596 --> 01:00:40.471
and listen to LBJ tell you that,

01:00:40.556 --> 01:00:44.308
"Violence never accomplishes anything,
my fellow Americans."

01:00:44.393 --> 01:00:48.062
And the honky drafting you out of school
to go fight in Vietnam.

01:00:48.147 --> 01:00:50.481
If you don't want any trouble,

01:00:50.566 --> 01:00:53.734
keep your filthy white hands
off our beautiful black skin.

01:00:53.819 --> 01:00:55.488
- Keep them off!
- [CROWD CHEERING WILDLY]

01:00:55.988 --> 01:01:00.241
NINA: <i>I am just one of the people</i>
<i>who is sick of the social order,</i>

01:01:00.326 --> 01:01:03.786
<i>sick of the establishment,
sick to my soul of it all.</i>

01:01:03.871 --> 01:01:07.873
<i>To me, America's society
is nothing but a cancer,</i>

01:01:07.958 --> 01:01:11.502
<i>and it must be exposed
before it can be cured.</i>

01:01:11.587 --> 01:01:12.920
<i>I am not the doctor to cure it.</i>

01:01:13.005 --> 01:01:16.674
<i>All I can do is expose the sickness.</i>

01:01:16.759 --> 01:01:18.509
[PEOPLE CLAMORING]

01:01:18.594 --> 01:01:21.262
Are you ready, black people?

01:01:21.347 --> 01:01:22.723
CROWD: Yeah!

01:01:23.932 --> 01:01:25.308
Are you ready, black people?

01:01:25.393 --> 01:01:26.600
CROWD: Yeah!

01:01:26.685 --> 01:01:28.019
MEN: [SINGING] <i># Are you ready? #</i>

01:01:28.104 --> 01:01:31.023
- Are you really ready?
- CROWD: Yeah!

01:01:31.565 --> 01:01:33.857
ANDY: <i>She wanted to align herself</i>

01:01:33.942 --> 01:01:37.945
with the extreme terrorist militants
who were influencing her.

01:01:38.030 --> 01:01:40.573
<i>And after all of these meetings
with all these people,</i>

01:01:40.658 --> 01:01:41.657
<i>she would come to me and,</i>

01:01:41.742 --> 01:01:45.286
<i>"Let's get the guns.
Let's poison the reservoir."</i>

01:01:45.371 --> 01:01:48.164
<i>All sorts of violent terrorist acts.</i>

01:01:48.249 --> 01:01:53.419
Are you ready to call the wrath
of black gods... black magic...

01:01:53.504 --> 01:01:54.503
CROWD: Yeah!

01:01:54.588 --> 01:01:56.004
...to do your bidding?

01:01:56.089 --> 01:01:57.965
NINA: <i>Black people are never</i>
<i>going to get their rights</i>

01:01:58.050 --> 01:02:00.426
<i>unless they have their own separate state.</i>

01:02:00.511 --> 01:02:03.887
<i>And if we'd have armed revolution,
there'd be a lot of blood.</i>

01:02:03.972 --> 01:02:05.973
<i>I think we'd have that separate state.</i>

01:02:06.058 --> 01:02:09.977
Are you ready to smash white things?

01:02:10.062 --> 01:02:12.730
CROWD: Yeah!

01:02:12.815 --> 01:02:14.773
To burn buildings, are you ready?

01:02:14.858 --> 01:02:16.900
CROWD: Yeah!

01:02:16.985 --> 01:02:18.986
ROGER: <i>At a certain point,</i>
<i>Nina started to play</i>

01:02:19.071 --> 01:02:21.947
<i>only political songs and nothing else,</i>

01:02:22.032 --> 01:02:23.657
<i>and that started to hurt her career.</i>

01:02:23.742 --> 01:02:26.160
<i>That became a problem to book her,</i>

01:02:26.245 --> 01:02:27.953
because promoters
were a little bit afraid that

01:02:28.038 --> 01:02:32.416
it might only be the political message
that you were getting.

01:02:32.501 --> 01:02:35.336
Are you ready to kill if necessary?

01:02:35.421 --> 01:02:37.171
CROWD: Yeah!

01:02:37.256 --> 01:02:38.922
Is your mind ready?

01:02:39.007 --> 01:02:40.007
CROWD: Yeah!

01:02:40.092 --> 01:02:42.426
- Is your body ready?
- CROWD: Yeah!

01:02:42.511 --> 01:02:46.013
NINA: <i>If I'd had my way,</i>
<i>I'd have been a killer.</i>

01:02:46.098 --> 01:02:48.849
<i>I would have had guns,
and I would have gone to the South</i>

01:02:48.934 --> 01:02:52.395
<i>and gave them violence for violence,
shotgun for shotgun,</i>

01:02:52.480 --> 01:02:54.021
<i>but my husband told me...</i>

01:02:54.106 --> 01:02:56.565
<i>I didn't know anything about guns,
and he refused to teach me,</i>

01:02:56.650 --> 01:02:59.193
<i>and the only thing I had was music,
so I obeyed him.</i>

01:02:59.278 --> 01:03:02.655
<i>But if I'd had my way,
I wouldn't be sitting here today.</i>

01:03:02.740 --> 01:03:04.698
<i>I'd be probably dead.</i>

01:03:04.783 --> 01:03:07.160
Are you really, really, really ready?

01:03:07.245 --> 01:03:08.786
CROWD: Yeah!

01:03:08.871 --> 01:03:11.330
ANDY:
<i>She's putting down the white people...</i>

01:03:11.415 --> 01:03:14.583
[MIMICS DOG] <i>I mean,</i>
<i>you know, like a barking dog,</i>

01:03:14.668 --> 01:03:17.503
<i>but she still wanted all the good things.</i>

01:03:17.588 --> 01:03:24.135
Whenever she'd see, like, Aretha Franklin
and Gladys Knight and all of these people

01:03:24.220 --> 01:03:29.682
on the prime television shows,
she, of course, was very upset because

01:03:29.767 --> 01:03:34.187
<i>she wasn't able to get on to these shows
because of her reputation.</i>

01:03:34.272 --> 01:03:39.317
It got so that there wasn't that much work
and the expenses were high.

01:03:39.402 --> 01:03:42.778
<i>It was cutting the legs out
from all the work that I had done.</i>

01:03:42.863 --> 01:03:44.572
- See you later.
- [CROWD CHEERING]

01:03:44.657 --> 01:03:46.324
I'll see you later.

01:03:46.409 --> 01:03:47.408
LISA: <i>I remember my dad</i>

01:03:47.493 --> 01:03:50.411
<i>complaining about the fact that
she never stopped speaking out,</i>

01:03:50.496 --> 01:03:52.538
<i>but that's who she was.</i>

01:03:52.623 --> 01:03:53.831
<i>It was okay when you were onstage.</i>

01:03:53.916 --> 01:03:55.291
<i>It's okay 'cause you let it all hang out,</i>

01:03:55.376 --> 01:03:57.585
and then when the show ends
and the lights go out,

01:03:57.670 --> 01:03:59.587
"Okay, let's put the monkey
back in the cage,

01:03:59.672 --> 01:04:02.466
and eat your banana and,
you know, just behave yourself."

01:04:03.133 --> 01:04:06.093
<i>It was like she was penalized and punished</i>

01:04:06.178 --> 01:04:08.637
<i>for being herself.</i>

01:04:08.722 --> 01:04:14.059
<i>That's a very painful, lonely place to be.</i>

01:04:14.144 --> 01:04:15.143
[TAPE ROLLING]

01:04:15.228 --> 01:04:16.604
INTERVIEWER: <i>Good evening.</i>

01:04:16.689 --> 01:04:20.816
<i>Tonight my guest in the studio with me
